          "text": "## 3 Approaches for Web Interface\n\nBased on your requirements (full feature parity, shared sessions, local-only server, separate command), here are three approaches:\n\n---\n\n### Approach A: Direct FastAPI Integration (Recommended)\n\n**Architecture**: Add FastAPI as a new entrypoint module alongside the TUI. The web app imports the same services and domain modules.\n\n**Structure**:\n```\nsrc/agent_tui/\n├── entrypoints/\n│   ├── app.py          # TUI entrypoint (existing)\n│   └── web.py          # FastAPI entrypoint (new)\n├── services/\n│   ├── adapter.py      # TUI adapter (existing)\n│   └── web_adapter.py  # Web adapter (new)\n└── web/                # Web-specific code (new)\n    ├── static/         # Tailwind CSS, HTMX, Alpine\n    └── templates/      # Jinja2 templates\n```\n\n**Pros**:\n- Fastest to implement — reuses existing domain and services directly\n- No abstraction overhead\n- Easiest to maintain feature parity\n\n**Cons**:\n- Web code is coupled to the agent-tui package structure\n- Less separation of concerns\n\n---\n\n### Approach B: Service Layer Extraction\n\n**Architecture**: Extract a shared \"core\" package that both TUI and web depend on. The web interface is a separate module that imports from core.\n\n**Structure**:\n```\nsrc/\n├── agent_tui_core/     # New: protocol, adapters, session store\n│   ├── domain/\n│   └── services/\n├── agent_tui/          # TUI depends on core\n└── agent_tui_web/      # Web depends on core\n```\n\n**Pros**:\n- Cleanest separation of concerns\n- Web could theoretically be its own package\n- Forces cleaner API boundaries\n\n**Cons**:\n- Requires refactoring existing code\n- More upfront work\n- May be overkill for a local-only tool\n\n---\n\n### Approach C: HTTP API Layer (Overkill for Local)\n\n**Architecture**: The TUI runs an HTTP server; the web interface is a pure client that talks to it.\n\n**Pros**:\n- Web interface could be completely separate (even hosted)\n- Single agent instance serves multiple UIs\n\n**Cons**:\n- Massive over-engineering for local-only use\n- Latency overhead for local communication\n- Complicates the architecture significantly\n\n---\n\n## My Recommendation: **Approach A**\n\nFor your use case (local-only, single user, feature parity), Approach A is the pragmatic choice. The TUI and web will share the same database, same services, and same protocol — the only difference is the presentation layer.\n\nThe adapter pattern makes this clean:\n- `AgentAdapter` → dispatches to TUI widgets\n- `WebAdapter` → dispatches to WebSocket/SSE connections\n\n**Does this direction look right to you?** If yes, I'll proceed to the detailed design sections.",
